414 trustee for the person for whose benefit the payment was made and must be held in that
425 account together with interest if any. If money is paid by check, share draft or money
436 order, the payee shall instruct the payor to make the instrument payable to the financial
447 institution or credit union into which it is to be deposited and to include on the
458 instrument the name of the mortuary trustee and the person for whose benefit the
469 payment was made.
7 B. The payee shall deposit the money in either a federally insured deposit or share
8 account or a trust account; the type of account must be disclosed to the payor or the
9 payor's representative and a deposit in a trust account may be invested in or used to
10 purchase only the following:
11 (1) Federally insured deposit or share accounts;
12 (2) Securities issued, insured or guaranteed by the United States or by any agency
13 or corporate or other instrumentality of the United States;
14 (3) Municipal securities that are exempt from registration under Title 32, section
15 16201, subsection 1; and
16 (4) Permanent life insurance, other than variable life insurance and annuities, from
17 an insurer authorized to transact insurance in this State, subject to the provisions
18 of Title 24‑A, chapter 27. A payee or mortuary trustee may not receive any
19 commission, fee or other consideration from an insurer in connection with the
20 procurement or purchase of insurance permitted by this subparagraph.
21 Except for fees allowed by this section, all investments made with trust assets remain
22 trust assets.
23 C. Within 30 days after the deposit of funds by the payee, the financial institution or
24 credit union shall provide a written confirmation of the deposit, including the amount
25 deposited, to the payor or the payor's legal representative. Nothing in this This section
26 may not be construed to prevent the direct transfer of these funds to another financial
27 institution or credit union by payee transfer, by financial institution or credit union
28 merger or consolidation or by operation of law, provided that as long as within 30 days
29 after the direct transfer of the funds, the recipient financial institution or credit union
30 shall provide provides a written confirmation of the deposit, including the amount
31 deposited, to the payor or the payor's legal representative.
32 D. The agreement must be in writing and a copy must be furnished to the payor or the
33 payor's legal representative by the payee when the agreement is executed. The
34 agreement may be revocable or irrevocable; however, if irrevocable, there must be a
35 provision to allow for the transfer of the account by the appointment of successor
36 trustees. The agreement must clearly state the name of the initial financial institution
37 or credit union into which the money will be deposited and must direct the payor to
38 send a copy of the agreement to the named financial institution or credit union. The
39 agreement must clearly state terms providing for disposition of excess funds after
40 funeral goods and services have been provided. The agreement must clearly state any
41 fees that may be charged against the account; fees must be reasonable, as defined by
42 the board, and may be charged only:
43 (1) Upon transfer of the account by the appointment of a successor trustee;
44 (2) Upon revocation of the agreement if the agreement is revocable; and
