1 (3) For the actual financial and tax administration of the account.
2 The payee shall maintain a complete record of the deposit of all funds, including
3 principal and interest. The record must be available for inspection by the payor, the
4 payor's legal representative, the commissioner's designee or an inspector for the board
5 and must contain the name and address of the financial institution or credit union
6 currently in possession of the funds and the dates and amounts of deposits.
7 E. The funds may be directed by the payee to another financial institution or credit
8 union or directed back to the payor or the payor's legal representative, if otherwise
9 lawful and permitted by contract, on written instructions of the payor or the payor's
10 legal representative. The funds may only be withdrawn by the payee on presentation
11 of a certified copy of the death certificate of the person for whose benefit the funds
12 were paid, in which event they must be used in accordance with the agreement.
13 Sec. 4. 32 MRSA §1401, sub-§1-A, as enacted by PL 2003, c. 109, §3, is amended
14 to read:
15 1-A. Plan funded with mortuary trust agreement and proceeds of life insurance
16 policy. A prearranged funeral or burial plan agreement may be funded with a mortuary
17 trust agreement that receives the proceeds of a life insurance policy in accordance with this
18 subsection.
19 A. During a person's lifetime, a person or that person's legal representative may enter
20 into an agreement that services will be performed or personal property will be delivered
21 in connection with the disposition of that person's body after death by:
22 (1) Assigning the mortuary trustee as owner and beneficiary of a life insurance
23 policy payable to the mortuary trustee upon that person's death; or
24 (2) Designating the mortuary trustee as a beneficiary of a life insurance policy
25 payable to the mortuary trustee upon that person's death.
26 B. An agreement under paragraph A must be in writing and a copy must be furnished
27 to the person or the person's legal representative by the mortuary trustee when the
28 agreement is executed. The agreement may be revocable or irrevocable; however, if
29 the agreement is irrevocable, there must be a provision to allow for the transfer of the
30 trust account by the appointment of successor trustees. The agreement must clearly
31 state terms providing for disposition of excess funds after funeral goods and services
32 have been provided. The agreement must clearly state any fees that may be charged
33 against the trust account. Fees must be reasonable, as defined by the board, and may
34 be charged only:
35 (1) Upon transfer of a trust account by the appointment of a successor trustee;
36 (2) Upon revocation of the agreement if the agreement is revocable; and
37 (3) For the actual financial and tax administration of the trust account.
38 C. The mortuary trustee shall maintain a complete record of a trust account established
39 under this subsection. The record must be available for inspection by the person, the
40 person's legal representative, the commissioner's designee or an inspector for the board.
41 This subsection may not be construed to alter the terms of a life insurance policy or
42 supersede any law governing the regulation of life insurance policies.
